default&#xa0;
defaultSpecific Pointsdefault&#xa0;
defaultQ1
default              
defaultAre crimes being recorded by the police when they should be? Are crimes being categorised correctly?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe general feeling which PCCs expressed
default, based on internal and external 
defaultchecks, was that
default crimes were being recorded and categorised correctly
default on the whole
default, within the
defaultir areas and within the
default limitations imposed by the system
default and the nature of statistics themselves.
default  However, human error and a number of the other issues addresse
defaultd at Q2 do lead to discrepancies, but as
default noted 
defaultat Q3
default, there are a number of checks and balances incorporated in the system already to try to ensure that recording and categorisation is accurate
default, although the nature of checks and balances can vary.  Taken t
defaultogether this means 
defaultthat there are some inconsistencies nationally and some dangers inherent in direct comparisons of raw data.
default   
defaultSome PCCs are also concerned that b
defaultudget cuts might impact on resources dedicated to quality control
default, and some PCCs feel that t
defaulthe whole system is too process based and does not taken enough account of victims’ views and needs, or allow for a common-sense approach
default.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ2
default              
defaultWhat are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?
default&#xa0;
defaultA number of factors have been suggested by PCCs.  One of the key issues identified is the short time slot allowed under the rules for officers to record an incident as a crime, which puts pressure on them 
defaultto make a judgement, 
defaultwithout sufficient time to con
defaultsider all the circumstances, and especially the victim’s wishes.
default&#xa0;
defaultOther factors suggested include human error,
default subjective interpretation, complexity of HO Counting Rules and
default lack of knowledge (particularly in relation to rarer types of crime
default, or recording 
defaultof multiple crimes arising from one incident
default),
default 
defaultthe bureaucracy of the process itself (which can result in short cuts being taken)
default, organisational culture (particularly around compliance issues, such as reluctance to challenge fellow officers), and level of
default scrutiny.  Several respondents also noted th
defaultat targets can encourage perverse incentives, but also noted that the trend generally both from Government and PCCs is to move away from targets which has helped the problem of ‘gaming’ to meet ‘quotas’.  But th
defaultere is still some feeling that the general pressure to show reduced rates of crime might still be leading to 
defaultsome down-grading of crime incidents to non-crime incidents, such as ASB. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ3
default              
defaultAre the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for 
defaultrecording crime function effectively and accurately?
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are a significant number of quality control checks already in place, although the nature and depth of scrutiny can vary from force to force.  However, typically as a minimum, these would include i
defaultnternal audit, crime registrar, external checks, such as periodic HMIC inspection, 
defaulttriangulation with other data, 
defaultand a degree of oversight from force management board and PCC. 
default  
defaultMuch depends on the quality of the audit, although s
defaultome forces 
defaultalso 
defaultinclude a
defaultdditional checks, such as external audit, dip sampling of crime recording and categorisation examples, additional levels of internal control process, or
default 
defaultIT systems which 
defaultflag
default erroneous data.
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultGreater transparency can also play a role in raising standards
default and 
defaulthighlighting areas of concern – although it should be noted that there remain concerns about the extent to which data is truly comparable, for reasons already noted, and whether comparison of this nature is desirable, given the more local focus of PCC
defaults.  Ultimately, it is for PCCs to hold the force to account (through the Chief Constable), and they will be concerned to ensure that crime recording meets local needs and expectations (see Q6 below).
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ4
default              
defaultHas enough been done to ensure the integrity of cri
defaultme data? What more should be done?
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is a balanc
defaulte to be struck between accuracy
default and the cost of quality control mechanisms
default, and some PCCs raised concerns about whether existing checks are sustainable in the current financial climate.  
defaultThe anticipated 
defaultHMIC Data Quality Inspection should throw some interesting light on 
defaultwhat more could be done
default, and some PCC respondees suggested 
defaultthat new mobile technology may help, or perhaps more training
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, a 
defaultmore fundamental debate may be
default needed 
defaulta
defaultbout whether di
defaultscrepancies from place to place are 
defaultan inevitable consequence of greater local accountability
default and responsiveness to victims (
defaultprovided the differences 
defaultthis generates 
defaultare transparent
default, understood
default and accounted for
default)
default, or whether 
defaultconsistency and comparability ar
defaulte paramount, 
defaultwhich would involve 
defaultgreater ce
defaultntralisation
default, s
defaulttricter rules
default and probably higher costs flowing from the greater bureaucracy involved.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ5
default              
defaultTo what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crim
defaulte by police forces?
default&#xa0;
defaultMost PCCs 
defaultwho 
defaultresponded felt that some confidence could be place
defaultd
default in the data
